<br>
Let me make it clear.  I do not &quot;believe&quot; in the theory as if it was &quot;gospel&quot;, as if it had just been handed down on stone tablets from on high.  I regard it as extremely plausible; I have run it through my head time after time and cannot see any flaws in the logic; I have been reading and reading to try and find a way to dismiss it and still cannot, (perhaps this is why I keep posting 'large articles' which make me look like a ranter.)<br>
<br>
Let me also make this clear. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>I do not want it to be true.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Just like everyone else here I want to see our species make the move into space. I want to see us develop new technology that will ensure the glorious future we deserve. I most certainly do not want to see us decline into some grim survivalist nightmare from a 'Mad Max' movie. I hope I am wrong and I want to be wrong.<br>
<br>
And maybe I am. I am not an expert, and maybe I am being really dumb here, but your point about &quot;it doesn't explain how per capita energy production is tied to industrial output&quot; just makes no sense to me!<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>The theory works by using the ratio of world energy production and world population. Energy-use per person is used as a measurable index of industrialization.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
That's it, plain and simple. Like a mathematical equation. If you add 2 + 2 + <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>x</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> + <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>y</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, what's the answer? Obviously it depends on the values of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>x</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>y</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
What Duncan does is to give specific values to the important parts of his equation based on the data available to him. It is hard to question the values he gives it seems to me.<br>
<br>
As I said earlier his theory has no need to explain any relationship (if one could be said to exist) between energy production per capita and industrial output, the theory is unaffected by any such consideration. (This is why I said I was bemused by your repeated raising of the point.)<br>
<br>
As for George Monbiot I thought we had covered that.  As I said I quoted the piece bacause I thought he made some good points, particularly the first paragraph about the way we humans &quot;see the world&quot; and our place in it, the nature of our consciousness.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>We live in a dream world. With a small, rational part of the brain, we recognize that our existence is governed by material realities, and that, as those realities change, so will our lives. But underlying this awareness is the deep semi-consciousness that absorbs the moment in which we live, then generalizes it, projecting our future lives as repeated instances of the present. This, not the superficial world of our reason, is our true reality. All that separates us from the indigenous people of Australia is that they recognize this and we do not.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->This seems chillingly true to me, and seems to resonate with the whole subject of our blind dependancy on oil, (and on how little coverage the looming crisis gets in the media.)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Unpopular Science<br>
For the past two years (since the publication of &quot;The End of Cheap Oil&quot; by Colin Campbell and Jean Laherrere in the March, 1998 Scientific American) I' ve been tracking discussion in the press about the imminent end of the petroleum era (see MuseLetter issues #81 and 91). Until quite recently there s been remarkably little to report. This fact in itself is remarkable. Industrial civilization runs on oil, and the emerging consensus among independent experts is that world production of oil will peak sometime between the years 2005 and 2010, with steep price increases and shortages following shortly thereafter. This should be disturbing and important news,worthy of hundreds of banner-headline articles in the world's newspapers. But for months I've looked in vain to find any mention of the subject whatever (other than the article just cited) in mainstream publications.<br>
<br>
(taken from)<br>
