you have a situaton that requires a nail to be driven in to a piece of wood one person uses a rock so the only energy he uses is personal, the other uses a hammer so there is the energy cost in fabricating the hammer, but after he has driven in the nail he still has the hammer. Meaning that for the second nail he will use only personal energy as well. That is the concept of capital. Efficiency is simply explained by the the comparisson of a model &quot;T&quot; Fords MPG rating to a modern Fords MPG rating the modern car does more work for less oil so if they have to do the same work then the modern car uses less oil, so my point is that annual per capita energy useage can only be used as an indicator when comparing situation of similar efficiency and capital otherwise it is useless, it's like saying 2+2+x+y =2+2+a+b when x and y are not equal to a and b.<br>
