I don't not understand sorry <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>electricity is the indispensable end-use energy for Industrial Civilization<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> electricity is a convienient method of transporting energy it is not the best but it's the one we use. It provides no energy of itself because it has to be made. Just like Hydrogen it is a carrier not a primary source<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>When energy quality is accounted for, then the importance of electricity becomes very, VERY clear. For example, if you want to heat your room, then 1 joule (J) of coal is 'equal' to 1 J of electricity. However, if you want to power up your TV, then 1 J of electricity is 'equal' to 3 J of coal!<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I thinks thats backwards space heating is one of the most inefficient uses for electricity other wise I don't know what he is trying to say<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>So if you're going to worry about energy, then don't lose sleep over oil, gas, and coal. Worry about the electric switch on the wall!<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Electricity is not an energy source it has to be produced unless this is a roundabout way of saying worry about efficiency.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You refer to the law of &quot;supply and demand&quot;. One thing that comes out of these musings (or so it seems to me) is how ineffective and in fact utterly hopeless it is to rely on economics, 'market forces', to break us out of this hold.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Market forces are the only way it will happen you can't sell something to someone if they don't want to buy &quot;making&quot; them will just create a backlash it requires education. I use buy in a loose sense not in the purchase sense like &quot;buy into&quot;.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Conservative estimates suggest that roughly four decades would be needed to redesign and replace the entire current fleet of automobiles and trucks, as well as power plants, heating and cooling equipment, and agricultural systems<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> replace all maybe, but it doesn't have to be total to have the desired effect. It isn't an all or nothing situation things can happen incrementally things are happening incrementally.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Then there's the question of whether alternative energies will be capable of serving the same functions as oil, even assuming they can be scaled up quickly enough<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> do they have to serve the same function? is the oil way the best way of doing things it is if you have oil but do you have to keep it that way. You can have the same material lifestyle in varied ways. Quickly enough for what.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>alternative fuels are, for the most part, incapable of replacing the highly concentrated energy that petroleum provides<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Double the efficiency half the required energy density, and exactly how much of that energy density is required. We use oil because it is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>cheap</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> and good (in and energy sense not pollution etc) not because it is the only thing to use.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Hydrogen is a net energy sink (there are no &quot;hydrogen reserves,&quot; and the process of production uses more energy than the burning of the resulting fuel provides)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Hydrogen is a carrier not a source just like electricity but it can be stored more efficiently as well.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>An industrial society based on renewables could never use energy at a per-capita rate even remotely approaching the levels Americans have become accustomed to<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Does It need to what are the efficiencies that can be obtained by the new systems it's not about how much energy is used it's about how much work is done.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Economists won't tell us because they themselves don't understand what a critical role energy plays in society<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->ad hominem maybe they just don't see how the per-capita energy consumption is directly and unchangeably tied to output (work) I don't either.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>For them, it's merely another resource governed by the all-knowing Market; if prices for any given resource go up, a substitute will appear<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Based on previous history they have no reason to doubt, why won't it happen with energy.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>According to White's Law,&quot;culture evolves as the amount of energy harnessed per capita per year is<br>
increased,<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong> or as the efficiency of the instrumental means of putting energy to work is increased.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
the bold part is what my whole point is about that is not covered in either the O.G. Theory or the discussion referenced they simply focus on the first part and ignore the last  if you are going to quote a law you can't ignore half of it, until the theory accounts for efficiency and capital then it is flawed. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=talche>Talche</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 88<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/4/03 8:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=185.topic&index=33>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.sighost.us/members/Tal/easter%20statue%20.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Our Eyes Wide Shut</span><hr size=1> Well dude, maybe you've got a point. Time will tell, be interesting to hear some new views here perhaps.<br>
